Jax-Span-2922"><span class=3D"mrow" id=3D"MathJax-Span-2923"><span class=3D=
"mi" id=3D"MathJax-Span-2924" style=3D"font-family: MathJax_AMS;">R</span><=
/span></span></span><span style=3D"display: inline-block; width: 0px; heigh=
t: 2.503em;"></span></span></span><span style=3D"display: inline-block; ove=
rflow: hidden; vertical-align: -0.073em; border-left: 0px solid; width: 0px=
; height: 1.004em;"></span></span></nobr><span class=3D"MJX_Assistive_MathM=
L" role=3D"presentation"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"=
><mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><mi mathvariant=3D"double-struck">R</mi></=
mrow></math></span></span>, it's easy to check that it is isomorphic to the=
 ring of all formal power series in countably many variables due to unique =
factorization) =E2=80=94 this is necessary to be able to do all the cool st=
uff mentioned in <a href=3D"https://codeforces.com/blog/entry/91632?#commen=
t-802482">this</a> comment.</p><p>Furthermore, Dirichlet series have Fourie=
r-transform-esque properties, in the sense that <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Dirichlet_series_inversion">Dirichlet series inversion</a> re=
sembles Fourier transforms. It is also interesting to note that L-functions=
 are just Dirichlet series of Dirichlet characters, which are related to gr=
oup characters used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_tra=
nsform_on_finite_groups">Fourier transforms on finite groups</a> =E2=80=94 =
a concise resource on this can be found <a href=3D"https://math.uchicago.ed=
u/~may/REU2016/REUPapers/Monson.pdf">here</a>. <a href=3D"https://empslocal=
.ex.ac.uk/people/staff/mrwatkin/zeta/NTfourier.htm">This webpage</a> is a g=
reat resource on the connections between number theoretical topics like Dir=
ichlet series and Fourier transforms, and anyone who likes FFT should go th=
rough some of these papers to truly appreciate the kind of theory that aris=
es at the junction of these two seemingly different fields.</p><p>At the ri=
sk of going off a tangent, L-functions are also one of the most important o=
bjects of study for modern number theory, being closely related to elliptic=
 curves and the Riemann hypothesis, to name a couple of famous applications=
 =E2=80=94 there is a lot of computational number theory that revolves arou=
nd L-functions as primitives.</p><p>Here are a few resources for anyone who=
